<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: FULLERTON; 
</P>
<P>
LEASING OF CAMPUS SPACE TO BE STUDIED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By TOM McQUEENEY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As a way to raise money, Fullerton School District officials next week will 
consider the specifics of leasing space on a school campus to businesses. 
</P>
<P>
School district officials would like to lease space for commercial activities 
on the Brookhurst Road side of Orangethorpe Elementary School while classes 
continue on the rest of the school grounds. 
</P>
<P>
The school board signed a contract last month with Newport Resource Management 
of Newport Beach to look at ways the commercially valuable land could be leased 
out, using the income to pay for some of the $4 million in backlogged 
maintenance needed for district schools and buildings. 
</P>
<P>
The study is expected to take about a month. If the board decides to lease out 
a portion of the land, some of the classroom buildings might be rebuilt on the 
quieter east end of the campus, school officials have said. 
</P>
<P>
"Leasing excess land is becoming a more prudent way for school districts to 
generate revenue," said Rush N. Hill II, chairman of Newport Resource 
Management. 
</P>
<P>
Instead of raising taxes, which voters have consistently said they don't want, 
school districts can earn money by finding land that commercial ventures might 
be interested in leasing on a long-term basis, Hill said. That way, he said, 
the district earns money but keeps the land in case it is needed later. 
</P>
<P>
Before state legislation in 1987, school districts earning money through such 
ventures usually had to give it to the state, Hill said. The new law, which 
encourages all school districts to begin joint public-private ventures on 
unused land, allows school districts to keep the lease income. 
</P>
<P>
School districts in California have leased out both vacant parcels and portions 
of school sites, such as large athletic fields, that were going unused, he 
said. The trick is finding a commercial venture that would fit in with 
activities permitted on the property. 
</P>
<P>
"We've not yet run into conditions where compatibility could not be achieved," 
Hill said. TOM McQUEENEY 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
