586 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
LA HABRA CONTRACTOR IS LATEST VICTIM OF VANDALS IN STRIKE; 
</P>
<P>
LABOR: TIRES ARE PUNCTURED AT A CONSTRUCTION YARD THAT DOES BUSINESS WITH OWL 
ROCK PRODUCT CO. DAMAGE TO THE STRUCK COMPANY AND ITS CUSTOMERS HAS BEEN 
ESTIMATED AT $500,000. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CRISTINA LEE, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
LA HABRA 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chuck Rizzuto is a union contractor who has no quarrels with anyone. But as a 
customer of the struck Owl Rock Product Co., he has become mired in its bitter 
fight with Local 12 of the Pasadena-based International Union of Operating 
Engineers. 
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday night, vandals with ice picks broke into the La Habra construction 
yard of Rizzuto's Republic Concrete Inc. and punctured every tire of the 11 
cars and trucks parked at the job site. On their way out, they sprayed-painted 
a warning message on a car: Owl Scab. 
</P>
<P>
La Habra police estimated the damage at $20,000. 
</P>
<P>
The incident followed a string of similar vandalism carried out by unknown 
people on Republic's job sites in Riverside and San Bernardino counties in the 
past three weeks, Rizzuto said. 
</P>
<P>
And Republic is not the only company that does business with Owl Rock to be 
struck by vandals. Similar incidents occurred recently in the yards of FST Sand 
and Gravel in Riverside, Gail Trucking Co. in Corona and other firms. Owl Rock 
officials estimated that recent vandalizing of Owl Rock job sites and of its 
customers and suppliers has totaled more than $500,000. 
</P>
<P>
Owl Rock is one of Southern California's major suppliers of construction 
materials. Ontario-based Mitsubishi Cement Corp., a unit of Mitsubishi Corp. of 
Tokyo, bought a 50% stake in Owl Rock last year. 
</P>
<P>
As with Rizzuto's firm, this is the first time vandals have broken into the FST 
job site, said Bill Medina, FST's general manager. And like Rizzuto, Medina was 
approached by union leaders weeks ago and told either to sever business ties 
with or find a non-union alternative to Owl Rock. 
</P>
<P>
But customers remain unfazed. "The incident will not affect our relationship 
with Owl Rock, because their pricing is cheaper," said Medina, adding that Owl 
Rock does about $15,000 a month in business with his firm. 
</P>
<P>
The troubles of Arcadia-based Owl Rock started five months ago, after its labor 
contract with the union expired. Negotiations on wages and benefits broke down 
in late September; the union went on strike. 
</P>
<P>
The 26,000-member union represents workers at 20 Owl Rock plants in Los 
Angeles, Orange, Riverside and San Bernardino counties. 
</P>
<P>
"We had vandalism, sabotage and picket-line violence from Sept. 29, the first 
day of the strike," said Mike Broome, Owl Rock's vice president of operations 
and assistant general manager. 
</P>
<P>
In some plants, conveyor belts were cut, tires slashed, acid poured into 
control panels and sand poured into diesel engines, he said. 
</P>
<P>
A few days later, Owl Rock stunned union workers by bringing in permanent 
replacements for the strikers. Then plant vandalism escalated, Broome said. 
</P>
<P>
David Paul Koppelman, general counsel of the union's Local 12, denied any link 
between the incidents and the union, saying his group does not sanction 
vandalism in the workplace. 
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Broome said that except for the San Bernardino and Azusa police 
departments, "We've been getting little cooperation from law enforcement to 
stop the violence in the plants." 
</P>
<P>
This week, Owl Rock took matters into its own hands. It hired John J. Knott, a 
private investigator and former Los Angeles Police Department detective, to 
track down the vandals. Knott said he will work closely with police 
investigators in the four counties. 
</P>
<P>
Owl Rock also dispatched security guards to monitor the job sites of customers 
who have been vandalized, including Rizzuto's firm. 
</P>
<P>
Owl Rock plans to hold a press conference, tentatively next week, to call 
attention to the recent violence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
OWL ROCK PRODUCT CO; STRIKES; UNIONS; VANDALISM; PROPERTY DAMAGE; CONSTRUCTION 
WORKERS -- LABOR RELATIONS; BUSINESS -- ORANGE COUNTY; VIOLENCE; THREATS 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
